John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
The independent schools of Scotland have many fine academic achievements behind them, and it has continued in 2018 with yet another number of outstanding exam results, which are also strengthened by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other efforts in the local environment.
With up to 30,000 students around Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best service level to their students and parents.
The independent schools try to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career and their position as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can put together and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we find that modern languages remain a popular topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language that he understands, it will hit his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it will strike the heart."
It is an important reminder that we cannot just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can look at the latest exam results this year that languages are highest in the statistics with the most passed exams in the independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received the high grade A.
The data collected by the 74 member schools of the SCIS showed that 72 percent of the students had the grade A in mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as important competences that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language is now perceived as a topic choice at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools and elsewhere.
A study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills carried out in 2014 found that among the reasons why employers could not fill job vacancies, 17 % had to do with lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
More job opportunities will in future require language skills, and these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career the young people choose, if they have learned another language, they have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The possibility of communicating directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a head start to the competitors.
According to a YouGov poll with over 4,000 respondents in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 percent.
Therefore, it is important to invest in language teaching for those who are children today.
When you can speak more languages, especially languages from developing countries, children have a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland there is a difference between schools in which languages are taught.
A number of schools focus on the more classic modern languages, while others teach in languages that are expected to be most important to the UK when looking forward to 2020, e.g. mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and provides them with the skills required for success regardless of what the future holds.
At present, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be really important for the future of the country in a global business environment, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should really be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this distinction to the young people of Scotland.
Il fout bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
