Harvard students take a course to get enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all bachelor students more sleep. The aim of the course is to counteract the growing macho culture where you study all night held up by large amounts of caffeine.
A researcher has shown that students at the world's best university often have little idea of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, has done the course, which he thinks is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a presentation on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"When the show was finished, a girl came up to me and said, "Why am I only told this now when I'm on the candidate?"
"She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is offered for the first time this year, explains how good sleep habits can improve your academic and sporting performance as well as your overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Director of the University's Health Department, says that the university has decided to offer the course after finding out that the students were in serious sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course consists of various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises there is a picture of a dorm where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, and how your sporting performance is affected by sleep deprivation and how important good sleep habits are.
In another part of the course, participants will hear about how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attacks, blood clots, depression and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to think about their daily habits by clicking on different icons on an interactive map of campus.
"We know that this will not change students' behaviour immediately.
But we think they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know how cigarettes affect your health," adds Professor Czeisler.
The pride in taking a "all-nighter" still exists, he says and adds that modern technology and increased pressure on the students have caused sleep deprivation to be a growing problem.
The "secret weapon" against stress, fatigue and anxiety is good and sufficient sleep, he said – it even counteracts weight gain, because lack of sleep makes the brain think that you are starving, why they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler organize the course last year when he took one of his courses at his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and made him work to make it a general course throughout the university.
He hopes that the next will be that all graduates will be offered a similar course before they continue their education.
