What is the Global Citizens Festival, and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
On Saturday, New York is the host city of the Global Citizens Festival – an annual music festival with a very impressive selection of artists and an equally impressive goal; to put an end to world poverty.
Global Citizens Festival will for the seventh time receive tens of thousands of people on Central Park’s large lawn, where they can look forward to concerts with Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes. At the same time, the festival will draw attention to the real goal of ending extreme poverty in 2030.
Global Citizen Festival started in 2012 and is an extension of the Global Powery Project, an international interest organisation that fights to end poverty by increasing the number of active opponents.
To receive a free ticket to the event (if you do not want to pay for a VIP ticket), concertgoers must perform a number of tasks or "actions". For example, do voluntary work, write to a world leader, make a phone call or another meaningful action that can draw attention to the goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen been, now that they have 12 years left to achieve the goal?
Does it create the idea of rewarding people with a free concert real change, or is it just another case of so-called "clicktivism" – i.e. people feel that they make a difference by signing a signature collection online or making a Twitter listing?
Global Citizen reports that since 2011, they have registered more than 19 million "actions" from their members aimed at different goals.
They believe that these actions have encouraged world leaders to make binding targets and political action equivalent to more than 37 billion dollars, which by 2030 are expected to have affected more than 2.25 billion people.
At the beginning of 2018, the group listed 390 objectives and actions that had become due to their actions, which amounted to over $10 billion, which had already been paid out or collected.
The Group estimates that so far these funds have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
One of the main objectives is The Power of Nutrition, which has started in England and is a collaboration between investors and strong people. They strive to "help children live out their full potential" and promise $35 million to address nutritional problems in Rwanda after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the help of the English government, donors, governments of other countries and world citizens like you, social injustice with malnutrition can become a footnote in the history books," said the ambassador for The Power of Nutrition, Tracey Ullman, to the audience at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that the UK Government has now promised funds to improve nutrition for mothers and children after receiving more than 5,000 online calls. This project, Power of Nutrition, will help five million mothers and children with advice on nutrition.
In answer to one of the website's frequently asked questions that read: "What makes you think that we can put an end to extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen wrote: "It will be a long and hard fight, and sometimes we will stumble and make mistakes.
But like the civil rights movement and the movements towards apartheid, we will succeed because we are stronger together."
