National Trust Sneams the Secret Life of Bats
New research from an area in the Scottish highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape when they hunt.
The hope is that the findings will shed light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and will help in the work on future conservation efforts.
The study is conducted by scientists from Scotland's National Trust and follows common bats, dwarf bats, long-eared bats and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed in carefully selected locations in the area to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
Data is also collected from staff from NTS and volunteers using handheld detectors.
In-depth analysis of the sound recordings will reveal the frequencies of the bats and show which species does what.
To produce a detailed landscape view of their behavior, a report and a map of the habitat are made.
NTS Rob Dewar Nature Conservation Adviser hopes that the results reveal which areas of habitat are most important and how they are used by the different species.
This knowledge can help to determine the benefits of habitat conservation efforts such as the establishment of meadows and how best to preserve forest areas for bats and similar species.
The number of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has fallen dramatically over the last 100 years.
They are threatened by buildings and urban expansion projects that affect shipowners and restrict their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a danger, as can fly traps, chemical treatment of building materials and pet attacks.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
But because they primarily hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use an advanced echolocation technique to find insects and fly around obstacles.
NTS, which is responsible for the conservation of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten trained experts who often collect data, inspect shipowners and sometimes make rescue operations.
The organization has even made Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the area around Thrave in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten of Scotland's bat species.
The caretaker of the area, David Thompson, says it is an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threeve we have a really good area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the good habitat.
Man there is much you don't know about bats, so work here and elsewhere can help to understand what they need to thrive."
He emphasizes the importance of looking for bats before making maintenance tasks on properties, as the destruction of a single nest can kill up to 400 females and young ones, thus risking the destruction of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish project manager for the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to give a hand.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we have, we don't know how the populations develop."
